# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fortification
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fortification/16th-century-bc] The **16th century BC** was a century that lasted from 1600 BC to 1501 BC.
[src:fortification/16th-century-bc] See: List of sovereign states in the 16th century BC.
[src:fortification/9th-century-bc] The **9th century BC** started the first day of 900 BC and ended the last day of 801 BC.
[src:fortification/9th-century-bc] It was a period of great change for several civilizations.
[src:fortification/9th-century-bc] In Africa, Carthage is founded by the Phoenicians.
[src:fortification/9th-century-bc] In Egypt, a severe flood covers the floor of Luxor temple, and years later, a civil war starts.
[src:fortification/9th-century-bc] It is the beginning of the Iron Age in Central Europe, with the spread of the Proto-Celtic Hallstatt culture, and the Proto-Celtic language.
[src:fortification/9th-century-bc] The major Olmec site of San Lorenzo Tenochtitlán in Mesoamerica declined in importance, after having been active since 15th century BC.
[src:fortification/9th-century-bc] See: List of sovereign states in the 9th century BC.
[src:fortification/abatis] An **abatis**, **abattis**, or **abbattis** is a field fortification consisting of an obstacle formed of the branches of trees laid in a row, with the sharpened tops directed outwards, towards the enemy.
[src:fortification/abatis] The trees are usually interlaced or tied with wire.
[src:fortification/abatis] Abatis are used alone or in combination with wire entanglements and other obstacles.
[src:fortification/abatis] Gregory of Tours mentions the use of abatis several times in his writing about the history of the early Franks.
[src:fortification/abatis] He wrote that the Franks ambushed and destroyed a Roman army near Neuss during the reign of Magnus Maximus with the use of an abatis.
[src:fortification/abatis] He also wrote that Mummolus, a general working for Burgundy, successfully used an abatis to defeat a Lombard army near Embrun.
[src:fortification/abatis] A classic use of an abatis was at the Battle of Carillon (1758) during the Seven Years' War.
[src:fortification/abatis] The 3,600 French troops defeated a massive army of 16,000 British and Colonial troops by fronting their defensive positions with an extremely dense abatis.
[src:fortification/abatis] The British found the defences almost impossible to breach and were forced to withdraw with some 2,600 casualties.
[src:fortification/abatis] Other uses of an abatis can be found at the Battle of the Chateauguay, 26 October 1813, when approximately 1,300 Canadian Voltigeurs, under the command of Charles-Michel de Salaberry, defeated an American corps of approximately 4,000 men, or at the Battle of Plattsburgh.
[src:fortification/abatis] An important weakness of abatis, in contrast to barbed wire, is that it can be destroyed by fire.
[src:fortification/abatis] Also, if laced together with rope instead of wire, the rope can be very quickly destroyed by such fires, after which the abatis can be quickly pulled apart by grappling hooks thrown from a safe distance.
[src:fortification/abatis] An important advantage is that an improvised abatis can be quickly formed in forested areas.
[src:fortification/abatis] This can be done by simply cutting down a row of trees so that they fall with their tops toward the enemy.
[src:fortification/abatis] An alternative is to place explosives so as to blow the trees down.
[src:fortification/abatis] Abatis are rarely seen nowadays, having been largely replaced by wire obstacles.
[src:fortification/abatis] However, it may be used as a replacement or supplement when barbed wire is in short supply.
[src:fortification/abatis] A form of giant abatis, using whole trees instead of branches, can be used as an improvised anti-tank obstacle.
[src:fortification/abwurfdach] A **removable roof** (*Abwurfdach*) was an easily dismantled construction that protected the curtain walls, cavaliers and bastions of several early modern European fortresses.
[src:fortification/abwurfdach] It was once believed that this construction was as old as the 12th century, but most modern historians maintain that the first removable roofs were constructed around 1550.
[src:fortification/abwurfdach] In the 19th century architectural historians, such as *August Essenwein*, developed the idea that, in the 12th century, the main buildings of a castle were universally topped by fighting platforms that were only covered by a "temporary" and easily dismantled protective roof.
[src:fortification/abwurfdach] More recent castle research also suggests that the majority of the Central European castles were not designed for large-scale sieges, but rather against minor or surprise attacks.
[src:fortification/abwurfdach] Since most castles were not built merely to provide the military function of a fortress, but at the same time were residences of the nobility, provisional roofs are unlikely to have been normal.
[src:fortification/abwurfdach] In addition, hardly anything is known about the roof structures of high medieval castles, since they were generally rebuilt in later times, or have not survived in the case of ruined castles.
[src:fortification/abwurfdach] From about 1550 onwards, however, there is historical evidence of the actual use of such roof structures in fortifications.
[src:fortification/abwurfdach] In the sphere of influence of the Franconian free imperial city of Nuremberg some removable roofs have survived to the present or been reconstructed.
[src:fortification/abwurfdach] For instance, some cavaliers and bastions at the imperial city fortress of Lichtenau at *Ansbach* are topped by such constructions.
[src:fortification/abwurfdach] Numerous corbels on the curtain walls indicate the intention to build removable roofs, but contemporary illustrations show that these plans did not come fully to fruition.
[src:fortification/abwurfdach] A bird's eye view at the time of the Thirty Years' War (around 1630, Swedish State Archives) portrays a defensive system with removable roofs on four of the five bastions.
[src:fortification/abwurfdach] The three cavaliers also have correspondingly open superstructures.
[src:fortification/abwurfdach] No roofs can be seen above the curtain walls.
[src:fortification/abwurfdach] This illustration view largely corresponds to the present state of this Renaissance fortress.
[src:fortification/abwurfdach] In the reconstruction of Nuremberg's city walls, that largely survived until the Second World War, several sections of the wall were re-covered in this way.
[src:fortification/abwurfdach] The posts of the roof trusses also rest on stone columns, which jut out of the wall line (**Mauerflucht**) or are placed on the cornices.
[src:fortification/abwurfdach] These Nuremberg forerunners were copied by other Franconian and Swabian imperial cities, for example in the fortifications of *Nördlingen* and the **Spitalbastei** bastion of *Rothenburg ob der Tauber*.
[src:fortification/abwurfdach] The history of this type of building remains largely unexplored by serious historians.
[src:fortification/abwurfdach] Even in contemporary Italian fortress construction, removable roofs or light roof structures have been documented e.g. at the *Fortezza da Basso* in Florence.
[src:fortification/abwurfdach] In the sixteenth century, Franconian military engineers leant heavily on Italian innovations.
[src:fortification/acropolis] An **acropolis** was the settlement of an upper part of an ancient Greek city, especially a citadel, and frequently a hill with precipitous sides, mainly chosen for purposes of defense.
[src:fortification/acropolis] The term is typically used to refer to the Acropolis of Athens, yet nearly every Greek city had an acropolis of its own.
[src:fortification/acropolis] The term derives from the homonymous Greek word "Ακρόπολις", composed from "akron" (ἄκρον), which means "top", and "polis" (πόλις), which means "city".
[src:fortification/acropolis] Acropolises were used as religious centers and places of worship, forts, and places in which the royal and high-status resided.
[src:fortification/acropolis] Acropolises became the nuclei of large cities of classical ancient times, and served as important centers of a community.
[src:fortification/acropolis] Some well-known acropolises have become the centers of tourism in the present day, and they are a rich source of archaeological information of ancient Greece, especially, the Acropolis of Athens.
[src:fortification/acropolis] The plural of *acropolis* (ακρόπολη) is *acropolises*, also commonly as *acropoleis* and *acropoles*, and ακροπόλεις in Greek.
[src:fortification/acropolis] The term acropolis is also used to describe the central complex of overlapping structures, such as plazas and pyramids, in many Mayan cities, including Tikal and Copán.
[src:fortification/acropolis] Acropolis is also the term used by archaeologists and historians for the urban Castro culture settlements located in Northwestern Iberian hilltops.
[src:fortification/acropolis] It is primarily associated with the Greek cities of Athens, Argos (with Larisa), Thebes (with Cadmea), Corinth (with its Acrocorinth), and Rhodes (with its Acropolis of Lindos).
[src:fortification/acropolis] It may also be applied generically to all such citadels including Rome, Carthage, Jerusalem, Celtic Bratislava, Asia Minor, or Castle Rock in Edinburgh.
[src:fortification/acropolis] An example in Ireland is the Rock of Cashel.
[src:fortification/acropolis] In Central Italy, many small rural communes still cluster at the base of a fortified habitation known as *rocca* of the commune.
[src:fortification/acropolis] Other parts of the world have developed other names for the high citadel, or *alcázar*, which often have reinforced a naturally strong site.
[src:fortification/acropolis] Because of this, many cultures have included acropolises in their societies; however, they do not use the same name for them.
[src:fortification/acropolis] The acropolis of a city was used in many ways, with regard to ancient time and through references.
[src:fortification/acropolis] Because an acropolis was built at the highest part of a city, it served as a highly functional form of protection, a fortress, and was as well as a home to the royal of a city and a centre for religion through the worshipping of different gods.
[src:fortification/acropolis] There have been many classical and ancient acropolises, including the most commonly-known, Acropolis of Athens, as well as the Tepecik Acropolis at Patara, Ankara Acropolis, Acropolis of La Blanca, Acropolis at the Maya Site in Guatemala, and the Acropolis at Halieis.
[src:fortification/acropolis] The most famous example is the Athenian Acropolis, which is a collection of structures featuring a citadel on the highest part of land in ancient (and modern-day) Athens, Greece.
[src:fortification/acropolis] Many notable structures at the site were constructed in the 5th century BCE, including the Propylaea, Erechtheion, and the Temple of Athena.
[src:fortification/acropolis] The Temple is also commonly known as the Parthenon, which is derived from the divine Athena Parthenos.
[src:fortification/acropolis] There were often dances, music and plays held at the acropolis, which it served as a community centre for the city of Athens.
[src:fortification/acropolis] It became a prime tourist destination by the 2nd century AD during the Roman Empire and was known as "the Greece of Greece," as coined by an unknown poet.
[src:fortification/acropolis] Although originating in the mainland of Greece, use of the acropolis model quickly spread to Greek colonies such as the Dorian Lato on Crete during the Archaic Period.
[src:fortification/acropolis] The Tepecik Acropolis at Patara served as a harbor to nearby communities and naval forces, such as Antigonos I Monopthalmos and Demetrios Poliorketes, and combined land and sea.
[src:fortification/acropolis] Its fortification wall and Bastion date back to the Classical period.
[src:fortification/acropolis] The acropolis was constructed in the fourth century BCE by the Hekatomnids that ultimately led to its seizure in 334 BCE by Alexander the Great.
[src:fortification/acropolis] The acropolis contributed significantly to the overall development that took place during the Hellenistic empires.
[src:fortification/acropolis] This acropolis was the earliest place of settlement, probably dating back to the third millennium BCE.
[src:fortification/acropolis] During excavations that took place in 1989, ceramic items, terracotta figurines, coins, bone and stone objects were found that date to the fourth century BCE.
[src:fortification/acropolis] The fortification wall and bastion that are built at this acropolis uses a style of masonry, commonly known as the Greek word ἔμπλεκτον (meaning "woven").
[src:fortification/acropolis] This style of masonry was likely used for weight-bearing purposes.
[src:fortification/acropolis] The Acropolis at Halieis dates back to the Neolithic and Classical periods.
[src:fortification/acropolis] It included a fortified wall, sanctuary of Apollo (two temples, an altar, a race course), and necropolis (cemetery).
[src:fortification/acropolis] This acropolis was the highest point of fortification on the south edge at Halieis.
[src:fortification/acropolis] There was a small open-air cult space, including an altar and monuments.
[src:fortification/acropolis] The Ankara Acropolis, which was set in modern-day Turkey, is a historically prominent space that has changed over time through the urban development of the country from the Phrygian period.
[src:fortification/acropolis] This acropolis was well known as a spot for holy worshipping, and was symbolic of the time.
[src:fortification/acropolis] It has also been a place that has historically recognized the legislative changes that Turkey has faced.
[src:fortification/acropolis] The Acropolis of La Blanca was created in Guatemala as a small ancient Maya settlement and archaeological site that is located adjacent to the Salsipuedes River.
[src:fortification/acropolis] This acropolis developed as a place of residence for the city of La Blanca's rulers.
[src:fortification/acropolis] Its main period of usage was during the Classical period of 600 AD to 850 AD, as the city developed as a commercial place of trade among a number of nearby settlements.
[src:fortification/acropolis] The Mayan Acropolis site in Guatemala included a burial site and vaulted tombs of the highest status royal.
[src:fortification/acropolis] This funerary structure was integrated into this sacred landscape, and illustrated the prosperity of power between the royal figures of Pedras Negras in Guatemala.
[src:fortification/acropolis] Acropolises today have become the epicenters of tourism and attraction sites in many modern-day Greek cities.
[src:fortification/acropolis] The Athenian Acropolis, in particular, is the most famous, and has the best vantage point in Athens, Greece.
[src:fortification/acropolis] Today, tourists can purchase tickets to visit the Athenian Acropolis, including walking, sightseeing, and bus tours, as well as a classic Greek dinner.
[src:fortification/acropolis] Because of its classical Hellenistic and Greco-Roman style, the ruins of Mission San Juan Capistrano's Great Stone Church in California, United States has been called an American Acropolis.
[src:fortification/acropolis] The civilization developed its religious, educational, and cultural aspects of the acropolis, and is used today as a location that holds events, such as operas.
[src:fortification/acropolis] The analogy is also aided by the neoclassical architecture of the Columbia University campus, which was designed by McKim, Mead & White in the early 20th century.
[src:fortification/acropolis] Much of the modern-day uses of acropolises have been discovered through excavations that have developed over the course of many years.
[src:fortification/acropolis] For example, the Athenian Acropolis includes a Great Temple that holds the Parthenon, a specific space for ancient worship.
[src:fortification/acropolis] Through today's findings and research, the Parthenon treasury is able to be recognized as the west part of the structure (the Erechtheion), as well as the Parthenon itself.
[src:fortification/acropolis] Most excavations have been able to provide archaeologists with samples of pottery, ceramics, and vessels.
[src:fortification/acropolis] The excavation of the Acropolis of Halieis produced remains that provided context that dated the Acropolis at Halieis from the Final Neolithic period through the first Early Helladic period.
[src:fortification/admiralty-scaffolding] Of a number of similar designs, obstacle *Z.1* was by far the most common.
[src:fortification/admiralty-scaffolding] This design comprised upright tubes 9 feet (2.7 m) high and 4 feet 10 inches (1.5 m) apart, connected by up to four horizontal tubes.
[src:fortification/admiralty-scaffolding] Each upright was braced by a pair of diagonal tubes, at approximately 45°, to the rear.
[src:fortification/admiralty-scaffolding] 20-foot (6 m) wide sections were assembled and carried to the sea to be placed in position at the half tide mark as an obstacle to boats.
[src:fortification/admiralty-scaffolding] However, trials found that a 250-ton barge at 5+1⁄2 knots (6.3 mph; 10.2 km/h) or an 80-ton trawler at 7+1⁄2 knots (8.6 mph; 13.9 km/h) would pass through the obstacle unimpeded, and a trawler easily pulled out one bay with an attached wire rope.
[src:fortification/admiralty-scaffolding] Tests in October 1940 confirmed that tanks could only break through with difficulty.
[src:fortification/admiralty-scaffolding] As a result, Z.1 was adopted as an anti-tank barrier for beaches thought suitable for landing tanks.
[src:fortification/admiralty-scaffolding] As an anti-tank barrier, it was placed at or just above the high water point where it would be difficult for tanks to gain enough momentum to break through.
[src:fortification/admiralty-scaffolding] In some places, two sets of scaffolding were set up: one in the water against boats, and one at high water against tanks.
[src:fortification/admiralty-scaffolding] The problem of securing the barriers on sand was overcome by Stewarts & Lloyds' development of the "sword picket"– This device was later known at the Admiralty as the "Wallace Sword".
[src:fortification/admiralty-scaffolding] Barriers ranging in length from a couple of hundred feet to three miles were constructed, consuming 50% of Britain's production of scaffolding steel at an estimated cost of £6,600 per mile (equivalent to £320,000 today).
[src:fortification/admiralty-scaffolding] Despite this, many miles of Admiralty scaffolding were erected using more than 15,000 miles (24,000 km) of scaffolding tube.
[src:fortification/admiralty-scaffolding] After the war, the scaffolding obstructed swimmers, and was subsequently removed for scrap.
[src:fortification/admiralty-scaffolding] Remaining traces are very rare, but occasionally revealed by storms.
[src:fortification/advanced-work] An **advanced work**, **advance-work** or **advanced outwork** is a fortification or outwork in front of the main defensive building or castle.
[src:fortification/advanced-work] In the Middle Ages in the Holy Roman Empire, advanced works, known as ***Vorwerke*** (singular: *Vorwerk*), were commonly found in smaller villages that were located in front of the main castle.
[src:fortification/advanced-work] Within these advanced works often lived relatives of the knightly family whose ancestral seat was in the castle itself.
[src:fortification/advanced-work] As a result, the advanced works became manor houses and were known locally as *schlosses*.
[src:fortification/advanced-work] They were suitable for defending against minor attacks and offered the village population a degree of protection.
[src:fortification/advanced-work] In the case of major attacks they also acted as an early warning system for the castle.
[src:fortification/advanced-work] Because the advanced works were supposed to function autonomously, a link with agricultural estates was possible, such estates then became granges or *vorwerkenden Gutshöfen*.
[src:fortification/advanced-work] Later they also took over administrative tasks.
[src:fortification/advanced-work] Over the course of time these advanced works detached themselves from the castle and became independent estates.
[src:fortification/fortification] A **fortification** (also called a **fort**, **fortress**, **fastness**, or **stronghold**) is a military construction designed for the defense of territories in warfare, and is used to establish rule in a region during peacetime.
[src:fortification/fortification] The term is derived from Latin *fortis* ("strong") and *facere* ("to make").
[src:fortification/fortification] From very early history to modern times, defensive walls have often been necessary for cities to survive in an ever-changing world of invasion and conquest.
[src:fortification/fortification] Some settlements in the Indus Valley Civilization were the first small cities to be fortified.
[src:fortification/fortification] In ancient Greece, large cyclopean stone walls fitted without mortar had been built in Mycenaean Greece, such as the ancient site of Mycenae.
[src:fortification/fortification] A Greek *phrourion* was a fortified collection of buildings used as a military garrison, and is the equivalent of the Roman castellum or fortress.
[src:fortification/fortification] These constructions mainly served the purpose of a watch tower, to guard certain roads, passes, and borders.
[src:fortification/fortification] Though smaller than a real fortress, they acted as a border guard rather than a real strongpoint to watch and maintain the border.
[src:fortification/fortification] The art of setting out a military camp or constructing a fortification traditionally has been called "castrametation" since the time of the Roman legions.
[src:fortification/fortification] Fortification is usually divided into two branches: permanent fortification and field fortification.
[src:fortification/fortification] There is also an intermediate branch known as semipermanent fortification.
[src:fortification/fortification] Castles are fortifications which are regarded as being distinct from the generic fort or fortress in that they are a residence of a monarch or noble and command a specific defensive territory.
[src:fortification/fortification] Roman forts and hill forts were the main antecedents of castles in Europe, which emerged in the 9th century in the Carolingian Empire.
[src:fortification/fortification] The Early Middle Ages saw the creation of some towns built around castles.
[src:fortification/fortification] Medieval-style fortifications were largely made obsolete by the arrival of cannons in the 14th century.
[src:fortification/fortification] Fortifications in the age of black powder evolved into much lower structures with greater use of ditches and earth ramparts that would absorb and disperse the energy of cannon fire.
[src:fortification/fortification] Walls exposed to direct cannon fire were very vulnerable, so the walls were sunk into ditches fronted by earth slopes to improve protection.
[src:fortification/fortification] The arrival of explosive shells in the 19th century led to another stage in the evolution of fortification.
[src:fortification/fortification] Star forts did not fare well against the effects of high explosives, and the intricate arrangements of bastions, flanking batteries and the carefully constructed lines of fire for the defending cannon could be rapidly disrupted by explosive shells.
[src:fortification/fortification] Steel-and-concrete fortifications were common during the 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:fortification/fortification] The advances in modern warfare since World War I have made large-scale fortifications obsolete in most situations.
[src:fortification/fortification] From very early history to modern times, walls have been a necessity for many cities.
[src:fortification/fortification] Amnya Fort in western Siberia has been described by archeologists as one of the oldest known fortified settlements, as well as the northernmost Stone Age fort.
[src:fortification/fortification] In Bulgaria, near the town of Provadia a walled fortified settlement today called Solnitsata starting from 4700 BC had a diameter of about 300 feet (91 m), was home to 350 people living in two-story houses, and was encircled by a fortified wall.
[src:fortification/fortification] The huge walls around the settlement, which were built very tall and with stone blocks which are 6 feet (1.8 m) high and 4.5 feet (1.4 m) thick, make it one of the earliest walled settlements in Europe, but it is younger than the walled town of Sesklo in Greece from 6800 BC.
[src:fortification/fortification] Uruk in ancient Sumer (Mesopotamia) is one of the world's oldest known walled cities.
[src:fortification/fortification] The Ancient Egyptians also built fortresses on the frontiers of the Nile Valley to protect against invaders from adjacent territories, as well as circle-shaped mud brick walls around their cities.
[src:fortification/fortification] Many of the fortifications of the ancient world were built with mud brick, often leaving them no more than mounds of dirt for today's archeologists.
[src:fortification/fortification] A massive prehistoric stone wall dated to 3200 BC surrounded the ancient temple of Ness of Brodgar in Scotland.
[src:fortification/fortification] Named the "Great Wall of Brodgar", it was 4 m (13 ft) thick and 4 m (13 ft) tall.
[src:fortification/fortification] The wall had some symbolic or ritualistic function.
[src:fortification/fortification] The Assyrians deployed large labor forces to build new palaces, temples, and defensive walls.
[src:fortification/fortification] In Bronze Age Malta, some settlements also began to be fortified.
[src:fortification/fortification] The most notable surviving example is Borġ in-Nadur, where a bastion built around 1500 BC was found.
[src:fortification/fortification] Exceptions were few—notably, ancient Sparta and ancient Rome did not have walls for a long time, choosing to rely on their militaries for defense instead.
[src:fortification/fortification] Initially, these fortifications were simple constructions of wood and earth, which were later replaced by mixed constructions of stones piled on top of each other without mortar.
[src:fortification/fortification] In ancient Greece, large stone walls had been built in Mycenaean Greece, such as the ancient site of Mycenae (famous for the huge stone blocks of its 'cyclopean' walls).
[src:fortification/fortification] In classical era Greece, the city of Athens built two parallel stone walls, called the Long Walls, that reached their fortified seaport at Piraeus a few miles away.
[src:fortification/fortification] In Central Europe, the Celts built large fortified settlements known as oppida, whose walls seem partially influenced by those built in the Mediterranean.
[src:fortification/fortification] The fortifications were continuously being expanded and improved.
[src:fortification/fortification] Around 600 BC, in Heuneburg, Germany, forts were constructed with a limestone foundation supported by a mudbrick wall approximately 4 meters tall, probably topped by a roofed walkway, thus reaching a total height of 6 meters.
[src:fortification/fortification] The wall was clad with lime plaster, regularly renewed.
[src:fortification/fortification] The Oppidum of Manching (German: Oppidum von Manching) was a large Celtic proto-urban or city-like settlement at modern-day Manching (near Ingolstadt), Bavaria (Germany).
[src:fortification/fortification] The settlement was founded in the 3rd century BC and existed until c.
[src:fortification/fortification] It reached its largest extent during the late La Tène period (late 2nd century BC), when it had a size of 380 hectares.
[src:fortification/fortification] At that time, 5,000 to 10,000 people lived within its 7.2 km long walls.
[src:fortification/fortification] The oppidum of Bibracte is another example of a Gaulish fortified settlement.
[src:fortification/fortification] The term *casemate wall* is used in the archeology of Israel and the wider Near East, having the meaning of a double wall protecting a city or fortress, with transverse walls separating the space between the walls into chambers.
[src:fortification/fortification] These could be used as such, for storage or residential purposes, or could be filled with soil and rocks during siege in order to raise the resistance of the outer wall against battering rams.
[src:fortification/fortification] Originally thought to have been introduced to the region by the Hittites, this has been disproved by the discovery of examples predating their arrival, the earliest being at Ti'inik (Taanach) where such a wall has been dated to the 16th century BC.
[src:fortification/fortification] Casemate walls became a common type of fortification in the Southern Levant between the Middle Bronze Age (MB) and Iron Age II, being more numerous during the Iron Age and peaking in Iron Age II (10th–6th century BC).
[src:fortification/fortification] However, the construction of casemate walls had begun to be replaced by sturdier solid walls by the 9th century BC, probably due to the development of more effective battering rams by the Neo-Assyrian Empire.
[src:fortification/fortification] Casemate walls could surround an entire settlement, but most only protected part of it.
[src:fortification/fortification] The Romans fortified their cities with massive, mortar-bound stone walls.
[src:fortification/fortification] The most famous of these are the largely extant Aurelian Walls of Rome and the Theodosian Walls of Constantinople, together with partial remains elsewhere.
[src:fortification/fortification] These are mostly city gates, like the Porta Nigra in Trier or Newport Arch in Lincoln.
[src:fortification/fortification] Hadrian's Wall was built by the Roman Empire across the width of what is now northern England following a visit by Roman Emperor Hadrian (AD 76–138) in AD 122.
[src:fortification/fortification] A number of forts dating from the Later Stone Age to the British Raj are found in the mainland Indian subcontinent (modern day India, Pakistan, Bangladesh and Nepal).
[src:fortification/fortification] "Fort" is the word used in India for all old fortifications.
[src:fortification/fortification] Numerous Indus Valley Civilization sites exhibit evidence of fortifications.
[src:fortification/fortification] By about 3500 BC, hundreds of small farming villages dotted the Indus floodplain.
[src:fortification/fortification] Many of these settlements had fortifications and planned streets.
[src:fortification/fortification] The stone and mud brick houses of Kot Diji were clustered behind massive stone flood dykes and defensive walls, for neighboring communities bickered constantly about the control of prime agricultural land.
[src:fortification/fortification] While Dholavira has stone-built fortification walls, Harrapa is fortified using baked bricks; sites such as Kalibangan exhibit mudbrick fortifications with bastions and Lothal has a quadrangular fortified layout.
[src:fortification/fortification] Evidence also suggests fortifications in Mohenjo-daro.
[src:fortification/fortification] Even a small town—for instance, Kotada Bhadli, exhibiting sophisticated fortification-like bastions—shows that nearly all major and minor towns of the Indus Valley Civilization were fortified.
[src:fortification/fortification] The earliest Mauryan period brick fortification occurs in one of the stupa mounds of Lauria Nandangarh, which is 1.6 km in perimeter and oval in plan and encloses a habitation area.
[src:fortification/fortification] 2500 BC) in present-day south-east Afghanistan has defensive walls and square bastions of sun dried bricks.
[src:fortification/fortification] India currently has over 180 forts, with the state of Maharashtra alone having over 70 forts, which are also known as *durg*, many of them built by Shivaji, founder of the Maratha Empire.
[src:fortification/fortification] A large majority of forts in India are in North India.
[src:fortification/fortification] The most notable forts are the Red Fort at Old Delhi, the Red Fort at Agra, the Chittor Fort and Mehrangarh Fort in Rajasthan, the Ranthambhor Fort, Amer Fort and Jaisalmer Fort also in Rajasthan and Gwalior Fort in Madhya Pradesh.
[src:fortification/fortification] Arthashastra, the Indian treatise on military strategy describes six major types of forts differentiated by their major modes of defenses.
[src:fortification/fortification] Forts in Sri Lanka date back thousands of years, with many being built by Sri Lankan kings.
[src:fortification/fortification] With the outset of colonial rule in the Indian Ocean, Sri Lanka was occupied by several major colonial empires that from time to time became the dominant power in the Indian Ocean.
[src:fortification/fortification] The colonists built several western-style forts, mostly in and around the coast of the island.
[src:fortification/fortification] The first to build colonial forts in Sri Lanka were the Portuguese; these forts were captured and later expanded by the Dutch.
[src:fortification/fortification] The British occupied these Dutch forts during the Napoleonic wars.
[src:fortification/fortification] Most of the colonial forts were garrisoned up until the early 20th century.
[src:fortification/fortification] The coastal forts had coastal artillery manned by the Ceylon Garrison Artillery during the two world wars.
[src:fortification/fortification] Most of these were abandoned by the military but retained civil administrative officers, while others retained military garrisons, which were more administrative than operational.
[src:fortification/fortification] Some were reoccupied by military units with the escalation of the Sri Lankan Civil War; Jaffna fort, for example, came under siege several times.
[src:fortification/fortification] Large tempered earth (i.e. rammed earth) walls were built in ancient China since the Shang dynasty (c.
[src:fortification/fortification] 1600–1050 BC); the capital at ancient Ao had enormous walls built in this fashion (see siege for more info).
[src:fortification/fortification] Although stone walls were built in China during the Warring States (481–221 BC), mass conversion to stone architecture did not begin in earnest until the Tang dynasty (618–907 AD).
[src:fortification/fortification] The Great Wall of China had been built since the Qin dynasty (221–207 BC), although its present form was mostly an engineering feat and remodeling from the Ming dynasty (1368–1644 AD).
[src:fortification/fortification] In addition to the Great Wall, a number of Chinese cities also constructed defensive walls to defend their cities.
[src:fortification/fortification] Notable Chinese city walls include the city walls of Hangzhou, Nanking, the Old City of Shanghai, Suzhou, Xi'an and the walled villages of Hong Kong.
[src:fortification/fortification] The famous walls of the Forbidden City in Beijing were established in the early 15th century by the Yongle Emperor.
[src:fortification/fortification] The Forbidden City made up the inner portion of the Beijing city fortifications.
[src:fortification/fortification] In the United States, there are many examples of historical forts or fortified "stations" - the name depended on the region.
[src:fortification/fortification] This was a structure built for defense against primarily Indian attacks in frontier areas.
[src:fortification/fortification] While some forts were sometimes used by militias, state and federal military units, their primary purpose was for private or civilian defense.
[src:fortification/fortification] Sometimes a stockade would surround the building(s).
[src:fortification/fortification] During the Spanish Era several forts and outposts were built throughout the archipelago.
[src:fortification/fortification] Most notable is Intramuros, the old walled city of Manila located along the southern bank of the Pasig River.
[src:fortification/fortification] The historic city was home to centuries-old churches, schools, convents, government buildings and residences, the best collection of Spanish colonial architecture before much of it was destroyed by the bombs of World War II.
[src:fortification/fortification] Of all the buildings within the 67-acre city, only one building, the San Agustin Church, survived the war.
[src:fortification/fortification] The Ivatan people of the northern islands of Batanes built their so-called *idjang* on hills and elevated areas to protect themselves during times of war.
[src:fortification/fortification] These fortifications were likened to European castles because of their purpose.
[src:fortification/fortification] Usually, the only entrance to the castles would be via a rope ladder that would only be lowered for the villagers and could be kept away when invaders arrived.
[src:fortification/fortification] The Igorots built forts made of stone walls that averaged several meters in width and about two to three times the width in height around 2000 BC.
[src:fortification/fortification] The Muslim Filipinos of the south built strong fortresses called *kota* or *moong* to protect their communities.
[src:fortification/fortification] Usually, many of the occupants of these kotas were entire families rather than just warriors.
[src:fortification/fortification] Lords often had their own kotas to assert their right to rule, serving not only as military installations but as a palace for the local Lord.
[src:fortification/fortification] It is said that at the height of the Maguindanao Sultanate's power, the areas around Western Mindanao were blanketed with kotas and other fortifications to block the Spanish advance into the region.
[src:fortification/fortification] These kotas were usually made of stone and bamboo or other light materials and surrounded by trench networks.
[src:fortification/fortification] As a result, some of these kotas were easily burned or destroyed.
[src:fortification/fortification] With further Spanish campaigns in the region, the sultanate was subdued and a majority of kotas dismantled or destroyed.
[src:fortification/fortification] Kotas were not only used by the Muslims as defense against Spaniards and other foreigners, but also by renegades and rebels in defiance of other chiefs in the area.
[src:fortification/fortification] During the American occupation, rebels built strongholds and the datus, rajahs, or sultans often built and reinforced their kotas in a desperate bid to maintain rule over their subjects and their land.
[src:fortification/fortification] Many of these forts were destroyed by American expeditions, as a result, hardly any kotas stand to this day.
[src:fortification/fortification] During Muhammad's era in Arabia, many tribes made use of fortifications.
[src:fortification/fortification] Hoping to make several attacks at once, the confederates persuaded the Medina-allied Banu Qurayza to attack the city from the south.
[src:fortification/fortification] However, Muhammad's diplomacy derailed the negotiations, and broke up the confederacy against him.
[src:fortification/fortification] The well-organized defenders, the sinking of confederate morale, and poor weather conditions caused the siege to end in a fiasco.
[src:fortification/fortification] During the Siege of Ta'if in January 630, Muhammad ordered his followers to attack enemies who fled from the Battle of Hunayn and sought refuge in the fortress of Taif.
[src:fortification/fortification] The entire city of Kerma in Nubia (present day Sudan) was encompassed by fortified walls surrounded by a ditch.
[src:fortification/fortification] Archeology has revealed various Bronze Age bastions and foundations constructed of stone together with either baked or unfired brick.
[src:fortification/fortification] The walls of Benin are described as the world's second longest man-made structure, as well as the most extensive earthwork in the world by the *Guinness Book of Records, 1974*.
[src:fortification/fortification] The walls may have been constructed between the thirteenth and mid-fifteenth century CE or during the first millennium CE.
[src:fortification/fortification] Strong citadels were also built other in areas of Africa.
[src:fortification/fortification] Yorubaland for example had several sites surrounded by the full range of earthworks and ramparts seen elsewhere, and sited on ground.
[src:fortification/fortification] This improved the defensive potential of preexisting hills and ridges.
[src:fortification/fortification] Yoruba fortifications were often protected with a double wall of trenches and ramparts, and in the Congo forests concealed ditches and paths, along with the main works, often bristled with rows of sharpened stakes.
[src:fortification/fortification] Inner defenses were laid out to blunt an enemy penetration with a maze of defensive walls allowing for entrapment and crossfire on opposing forces.
[src:fortification/fortification] Between the 15th and 19th centuries, forts and walled cities were constructed on a large scale from the Senegal River to settlements of the Niger River.
[src:fortification/fortification] The types of fortification ranged from the tata to the ribat.
[src:fortification/fortification] Stone castles and fortified villages were evident in Ethiopia since the 13th century.
[src:fortification/fortification] In Southern Africa, urban centres were walled since the 13th century with notable examples at Mapungubwe and Great Zimbabwe.
[src:fortification/fortification] A military tactic of the Ashanti was to create powerful log stockades at key points.
[src:fortification/fortification] This was employed in later wars against the British to block British advances.
[src:fortification/fortification] Some of these fortifications were over a hundred yards long, with heavy parallel tree trunks.
[src:fortification/fortification] They were impervious to destruction by artillery fire.
[src:fortification/fortification] Behind these stockades, numerous Ashanti soldiers were mobilized to check enemy movement.
[src:fortification/fortification] While formidable in construction, many of these strongpoints failed because Ashanti guns, gunpowder and bullets were poor, and provided little sustained killing power in defense.
[src:fortification/fortification] Time and time again British troops overcame or bypassed the stockades by mounting old-fashioned bayonet charges, after laying down some covering fire.
[src:fortification/fortification] These cities were only rarely protected by simple stone walls and more usually by a combination of both walls and ditches.
[src:fortification/fortification] From the 12th century, hundreds of settlements of all sizes were founded all across Europe, which very often obtained the right of fortification soon afterward.
[src:fortification/fortification] The founding of urban centers was an important means of territorial expansion and many cities, especially in eastern Europe, were founded precisely for this purpose during the period of Ostsiedlung.
[src:fortification/fortification] These cities are easy to recognize due to their regular layout and large market spaces.
[src:fortification/fortification] The fortifications of these settlements were continuously improved to reflect the current level of military development.
[src:fortification/fortification] Unlike the Venetians, the Ottomans used to build smaller fortifications but in greater numbers, and only rarely fortified entire settlements such as Počitelj, Vratnik, and Jajce in Bosnia.
[src:fortification/fortification] Medieval-style fortifications were largely made obsolete by the arrival of cannons on the 14th century battlefield.
[src:fortification/fortification] Walls exposed to direct cannon fire were very vulnerable, so were sunk into ditches fronted by earth slopes.
[src:fortification/fortification] This placed a heavy emphasis on the geometry of the fortification to allow defensive cannonry interlocking fields of fire to cover all approaches to the lower and thus more vulnerable walls.
[src:fortification/fortification] The evolution of this new style of fortification can be seen in transitional forts such as Sarzanello in North West Italy which was built between 1492 and 1502.
[src:fortification/fortification] Sarzanello consists of both crenellated walls with towers typical of the medieval period, but also has a ravelin-like angular gun platform screening one of the curtain walls which is protected from flanking fire from the towers of the main part of the fort.
[src:fortification/fortification] Another example is the fortifications of Rhodes which were *frozen* in 1522 so that Rhodes is the only European walled town that still shows the transition between the classical medieval fortification and the modern ones.
[src:fortification/fortification] A manual about the construction of fortification was published by Giovanni Battista Zanchi in 1554.
[src:fortification/fortification] Fortifications also extended in depth, with protected batteries for defensive cannonry, to allow them to engage attacking cannons to keep them at a distance and prevent them from bearing directly on the vulnerable walls.
[src:fortification/fortification] The result was star shaped fortifications with tier upon tier of hornworks and bastions, of which Fort Bourtange is an excellent example.
[src:fortification/fortification] There are also extensive fortifications from this era in the Nordic states and in Britain, the fortifications of Berwick-upon-Tweed and the harbor archipelago of Suomenlinna at Helsinki being fine examples.
[src:fortification/fortification] Gone were citadels surrounding towns: forts were to be moved some distance away from cities to keep the enemy at a distance so their artillery could not bombard said urbanized settlements.
[src:fortification/fortification] From now on a ring of forts were to be built at a spacing that would allow them to effectively cover the intervals between them.
[src:fortification/fortification] The arrival of explosive shells in the 19th century led to yet another stage in the evolution of fortification.
[src:fortification/fortification] Star forts did not fare well against the effects of high explosives - intricate arrangements of bastions, flanking batteries, and the carefully constructed lines of fire for the defending cannon could be rapidly disrupted by explosive shells.
[src:fortification/fortification] Worse, the large open ditches surrounding forts of this type were an integral part of the defensive scheme, as was the covered way at the edge of the counterscarp.
[src:fortification/fortification] The ditch was extremely vulnerable to bombardment with explosive shells.
[src:fortification/fortification] In response, military engineers evolved the polygonal style of fortification.
[src:fortification/fortification] The ditch became deep and vertically sided, cut directly into the native rock or soil, laid out as a series of straight lines creating the central fortified area that gives this style of fortification its name.
[src:fortification/fortification] Wide enough to be an impassable barrier for attacking troops but narrow enough to be a difficult target for enemy shellfire, the ditch was swept by fire from defensive blockhouses set in the ditch as well as firing positions cut into the outer face of the ditch itself.
[src:fortification/fortification] The profile of the fort became very low indeed, its ditch protected by caponiers and surrounded by a gently sloping open area so as to eliminate possible cover for enemy forces, while the fort itself provided a minimal target for enemy fire.
[src:fortification/fortification] The entrypoint became a sunken gatehouse in the inner face of the ditch, reached by a curving ramp that gave access to the gate via a rolling bridge that could be withdrawn into the gatehouse.
[src:fortification/fortification] Deep passages and tunnel networks now connected the blockhouses and firing points in the ditch to the fort proper, with magazines and machine rooms deep under the surface.
[src:fortification/fortification] The guns, however, were often mounted in open emplacements and protected only by a parapet; both in order to keep a lower profile and also because experience with guns in closed casemates had seen them put out of action by rubble as their own casemates were collapsed around them.
[src:fortification/fortification] The new forts abandoned the principle of the bastion, which had also been made obsolete by advances in arms.
[src:fortification/fortification] The outline was a much-simplified polygon, surrounded by a ditch.
[src:fortification/fortification] These forts, built in masonry and shaped stone, were designed to shelter their garrison against bombardment.
[src:fortification/fortification] One organizing feature of the new system involved the construction of two defensive curtains: an outer line of forts, backed by an inner ring or line at critical points of terrain or junctions (see, for example, Séré de Rivières system in France).
[src:fortification/fortification] Traditional fortification however continued to be applied by European armies engaged in warfare in colonies established in Africa against lightly armed attackers from amongst the indigenous population.
[src:fortification/fortification] A relatively small number of defenders in a fort impervious to primitive weaponry could hold out against high odds, the only constraint being the supply of ammunition.
[src:fortification/fortification] However, the advances in modern warfare since World War I have made large-scale fortifications obsolete in most situations.
[src:fortification/fortification] In the 1930s and 1940s, some fortifications were built with designs taking into consideration the new threat of aerial warfare, such as Fort Campbell in Malta.
[src:fortification/fortification] Despite this, only underground bunkers are still able to provide some protection in modern wars.
[src:fortification/fortification] Many historical fortifications were demolished during the modern age, but a considerable number survive as popular tourist destinations and prominent local landmarks today.
[src:fortification/fortification] Instead field fortification rose to dominate defensive action.
[src:fortification/fortification] Unlike the trench warfare which dominated World War I, these defenses were more temporary in nature.
[src:fortification/fortification] This was an advantage because since it was less extensive, it formed a less obvious target for enemy force to be directed against.
[src:fortification/fortification] If sufficient power were massed against one point to penetrate it, the forces based there could be withdrawn and the line could be reestablished relatively quickly.
[src:fortification/fortification] Instead of a supposedly impenetrable defensive line, such fortifications emphasized defense in depth, so that as defenders were forced to pull back or were overrun, the lines of defenders behind them could take over the defense.
[src:fortification/fortification] Because the mobile offensives practiced by both sides usually focused on avoiding the strongest points of a defensive line, these defenses were usually relatively thin and spread along the length of a line.
[src:fortification/fortification] The defense was usually not equally strong throughout, however.
[src:fortification/fortification] The strength of the defensive line in an area varied according to how rapidly an attacking force could progress in the terrain that was being defended—both the terrain the defensive line was built on and the ground behind it that an attacker might hope to break out into.
[src:fortification/fortification] This was both for reasons of the strategic value of the ground, and its defensive value.
[src:fortification/fortification] This was possible because while offensive tactics were focused on mobility, so were defensive tactics.
[src:fortification/fortification] The dug-in defenses consisted primarily of infantry and antitank guns.
[src:fortification/fortification] Defending tanks and tank destroyers would be concentrated in mobile brigades behind the defensive line.
[src:fortification/fortification] If a major offensive was launched against a point in the line, mobile reinforcements would be sent to reinforce that part of the line that was in danger of failing.
[src:fortification/fortification] Thus the defensive line could be relatively thin because the bulk of the fighting power of the defenders was not concentrated in the line itself but rather in the mobile reserves.
[src:fortification/fortification] A notable exception to this rule was seen in the defensive lines at the Battle of Kursk during World War II, where German forces deliberately attacked the strongest part of the Soviet defenses, seeking to crush them utterly.
[src:fortification/fortification] The terrain that was being defended was of primary importance because open terrain that tanks could move over quickly made possible rapid advances into the defenders' rear areas that were very dangerous to the defenders.
[src:fortification/fortification] Thus such terrain had to be defended at all costs.
[src:fortification/fortification] For example, the Battle of the Hurtgen Forest in Germany during the closing stages of World War II is an excellent example of how difficult terrain could be used to the defenders' advantage.
[src:fortification/fortification] After World War II, intercontinental ballistic missiles capable of reaching much of the way around the world were developed, so speed became an essential characteristic of the strongest militaries and defenses.
[src:fortification/fortification] Missile silos were developed, so missiles could be fired from the middle of a country and hit cities and targets in another country, and airplanes (and aircraft carriers) became major defenses and offensive weapons (leading to an expansion of the use of airports and airstrips as fortifications).
[src:fortification/fortification] Mobile defenses could be had underwater, too, in the form of ballistic missile submarines capable of firing submarine launched ballistic missiles.
[src:fortification/fortification] Some bunkers in the mid to late 20th century came to be buried deep inside mountains and prominent rocks, such as Gibraltar and the Cheyenne Mountain Complex.
[src:fortification/fortification] On the ground itself, minefields have been used as hidden defenses in modern warfare, often remaining long after the wars that produced them have ended.
[src:fortification/fortification] Demilitarized zones along borders are arguably another type of fortification, although a passive kind, providing a buffer between potentially hostile militaries.
[src:fortification/fortification] Military airfields offer a fixed "target rich" environment for even relatively small enemy forces, using hit-and-run tactics by ground forces, stand-off attacks (mortars and rockets), air attacks, or ballistic missiles.
[src:fortification/fortification] Key targets—aircraft, munitions, fuel, and vital technical personnel—can be protected by fortifications.
[src:fortification/fortification] Aircraft can be protected by revetments, hesco barriers, hardened aircraft shelters and underground hangars which will protect from many types of attack.
[src:fortification/fortification] Larger aircraft types tend to be based outside the operational theater.
[src:fortification/fortification] Munition storage follows safety rules which use fortifications (bunkers and bunds) to provide protection against accident and chain reactions (sympathetic detonations).
[src:fortification/fortification] Weapons for rearming aircraft can be stored in small fortified *expense* stores closer to the aircraft.
[src:fortification/fortification] Aircrew and ground personnel will need protection during enemy attacks and fortifications range from culvert section "duck and cover" shelters to permanent air raid shelters.
[src:fortification/fortification] Soft locations with high personnel densities such as accommodation and messing facilities can have limited protection by placing prefabricated concrete walls or barriers around them, examples of barriers are Jersey barriers, T Barriers, or Splinter Protection Units (SPUs).
[src:fortification/fortification] Older fortification may prove useful such as the old 'Yugo' pyramid shelters built in the 1980s which were used by US personnel on 8 Jan 2020 when Iran fired 11 ballistic missiles at Ayn al-Asad Airbase in Iraq.
[src:fortification/fortification] Fuel is volatile and has to comply with rules for storage which provide protection against accidents.
[src:fortification/fortification] Fuel in underground bulk fuel installations is well protected though valves and controls are vulnerable to enemy action.
[src:fortification/fortification] Above-ground tanks can be susceptible to attack.
[src:fortification/fortification] Ground support equipment will need to be protected by fortifications to be usable after an enemy attack.
[src:fortification/fortification] Permanent (concrete) guard fortifications are safer, stronger, last longer and are more cost-effective than sandbag fortifications.
[src:fortification/fortification] Prefabricated positions can be made from concrete culvert sections.
[src:fortification/fortification] The British Yarnold Bunker is made from sections of a concrete pipe.
[src:fortification/fortification] Guard towers provide an increased field of view but a lower level of protection.
[src:fortification/fortification] Dispersal and camouflage of assets can supplement fortifications against some forms of airfield attack.
[src:fortification/fortification] Just as in colonial periods, comparatively obsolete fortifications are still used for low intensity conflicts.
[src:fortification/fortification] Such fortifications range in size from small patrol bases or forward operating bases up to huge airbases such as Camp Bastion/Leatherneck in Afghanistan.
[src:fortification/fortification] Forts in modern American usage often refer to space set aside by governments for a permanent military facility; these often do not have any actual fortifications, and can have specializations (military barracks, administration, medical facilities, or intelligence).
[src:fortification/fortification] However, there are some modern fortifications that are referred to as forts.
[src:fortification/fortification] These are typically small semipermanent fortifications.
[src:fortification/fortification] In urban combat, they are built by upgrading existing structures such as houses or public buildings.
[src:fortification/fortification] In field warfare they are often log, sandbag or gabion type construction.
[src:fortification/fortification] Such forts are typically only used in low-level conflicts, such as counterinsurgency conflicts or very low-level conventional conflicts, such as the Indonesia–Malaysia confrontation, which saw the use of log forts for use by forward platoons and companies.
[src:fortification/fortification] The reason for this is that static above-ground forts cannot survive modern direct or indirect fire weapons larger than mortars, RPGs and small arms.
[src:fortification/fortification] Fortifications designed to keep the inhabitants of a facility in rather than attacker out can also be found, in prisons, concentration camps, and other such facilities.
[src:fortification/fortification] Those are covered in other articles, as most prisons and concentration camps are not primarily military forts (although forts, camps, and garrison towns have been used as prisons and/or concentration camps; such as Theresienstadt, Guantanamo Bay detention camp and the Tower of London for example).
